Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) analysis demonstrated that CTF-PTZ was amorphous (Fig. 2
                        ). For determining the structural and binding characteristics of the obtained materials, the fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectra and 13C CP-MAS solid-state NMR were taken to ensure the structural of CTF-PTZ. The FT-IR spectra are presented in Fig. 3
                        . Comparing Fig. 3a and b, the carbonitrile band (CN) disappears at 2221 ​cm−1, and the absorption band appears at 1654 ​cm−1, indicating that the cyano-group almost completely disappears and the s-triazine rings have synthetized successfully which means successful synthesis of CTF-PTZ. Further structural analysis was verified by 13C CP-MAS solid-state NMR (Fig. 4
                        ). As expected, the chemical shift of methyl carbon appears at 29 ​ppm, each type of carbon in phenothiazine appears at 107, 115, 120, 141 and 164 ​ppm, respectively. The most important chemical shift of the 1,3,5-triazinyl appears at 177 ​ppm. Provided the structure, the polymer was characterized by gel permeation chromatography (GPC) to ensure the specific molecular weight of CTF-PTZ and the results show that the number-average molecular weight (Mn) and the weight-average molecular weight (Mw) of the polymer are 12938 and 15163 with polydispersity index (PDI) of 1.17. The moderate molecular weight and narrow PDI value means CTF-PTZ has a high degree of polymerization and its polymerization reaction is selectively controlled. Then, we performed Thermogravimetric Analysis (TGA) tests on CTF-PTZ and the results are shown in Fig. 5
                        . The CTF-PTZ samples are thermally stable up to 270 ​°C under a N2 atmosphere (only 5% weight loss). When the temperature exceeds 270 ​°C, there is obvious mass loss which may be caused by the destruction of rigid triazine ring in polymer molecule and the decrease of molecular weight. In conclusion, CTF-PTZ exhibits high-temperature resistance which can meet the application of daily and even high temperature conditions.

A more accurate pore size statistic was performed as shown in Fig. 6
                         by nitrogen adsorption/desorption measurement at 77 ​K. The pore diameter of CTF-PTZ is centered around 22 ​nm, meaning that this material is mainly mesoporous. Besides, the calculated BET surface area is 26.7 m2g-1. The morphology features of CTF-PTZ were characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM). The SEM images show that the CTF-PTZ polymer exhibits irregular agglomerated spherical particles and obvious pores (Fig. 7
                        ). As expected, the CTF-PTZ exhibits pore sizes primarily in the mesoporous size regime.

CTF-PTZ is a brownish-yellow powder and without fluorescence properties in solid state. However, when CTF-PTZ was dispersed in solvents, the solution presented strong fluorescence (Fig. 8
). Hence, we studied the solvent effect [41] on the fluorescence intensity of CTF-PTZ. We dispersed CTF-PTZ in acetonitrile (ACN), acetone, dimethylformamide (DMF), 1, 4-dioxane (DOX), chloroform, tetrahydrofuran (THF), H2O and ethanol (EtOH) to study its fluorescence sensing properties. Under the illumination of a 365 ​nm fluorescent lamp, we can see that the CTF-PTZ dispersed in different solvents exhibits fluorescence properties of different colors and intensities (Fig. 9
). The specific fluorescence intensity was obtained through experiments. As shown in Fig. 10
, CTF-PTZ dispersed in DOX shows the highest fluorescence peak compared with other solvents. Since CTF-PTZ in dioxane exhibits the strongest emission intensity among all solvents, the subsequent sensing experiments were carried out in dioxane.
